04670nam a22005655i 9780822393306DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223933067 a10.1515/97808223933062doi  a(DE-B1597)554660  a(OCoLC)809263589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aTP248.23b.L58 2012 7aSOC0020102bisacsh  aLC 560002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90662:77200aLively Capital :bBiotechnologies, Ethics, and Governance in Global Markets /cKaushik Sunder Rajan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b16 illustrations, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExperimental futures : technological lives, scientific arts, anthropological voices00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Capitalization of Life and the Liveliness of Capital -- t1. Prescription Maximization and the Accumulation of Surplus Health in the Pharmaceutical Industry -- t2. Value- Added Dogs and Lively Capital -- t3. Air's Substantiations -- t4. Taking Life: Private Rights in Public Nature -- t5. Rice Genomes: Making Hybrid Properties -- t6. Marx in New Zealand -- t7. AIDS Policies for Markets and Warriors -- t8. Diagnostic Liquidity -- t9. Transforming States in the Era of Global Pharmaceuticals -- t10. Biopolitics and the Informating of Environmentalism -- t11. Genomics Scandals and Other Volatilities of Promising -- t12. Desperate and Rational -- t13. Lively Biotech and Translational Research -- tEpilogue: Threads and Articulations -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLively Capital is an urgent and important collection of essays addressing the reconfigured relations between the life sciences and the market. Exploring the ground where social and cultural anthropology intersect with science and technology studies, prominent scholars investigate the relationship of biotechnology to ethics, governance, and markets, as well as the new legal, social, cultural, and institutional mechanisms emerging to regulate biotechnology. The contributors examine genomics, pharmaceutical marketing, intellectual property, environmental science, clinical trials, patient advocacy, and other such matters as they are playing out in North and South America, Europe, Africa, and Asia. Lively Capital is not only about the commercialization of the life sciences, but their institutional histories, epistemic formations, and systems of valuation. It is also about the lively affects-the emotions and desires-involved when technologies and research impinge on experiences of embodiment, kinship, identity, disability, citizenship, accumulation, and dispossession. At stake in the commodification of the life sciences are opportunities to intervene in and adjudicate matters of health, life, and death.Contributors. Timothy Choy, Joseph Dumit, Michael M. J. Fischer, Kim Fortun, Mike Fortun, Donna Haraway, Sheila Jasanoff, Wen-Hua Kuo, Andrew Lakoff, Kristin Peterson, Chloe Silverman, Elta Smith, Kaushik Sunder Rajan, Travis J. Tanner  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aBiotechnology industriesxFinance. 0aBiotechnologyxPolitical aspects. 0aBiotechnologyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aSunder Rajan, Kaushik, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393306zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393306423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393306.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DU